        {
            "blockname": "Learning in Practice",
            "name": "Challenges",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "subtitle": "The Practice Setting",
                    "space_after": true,
                    "components": [
                        {
                            "type": "text-paragraph",
                            "text": "The practice environment is primarily about meeting the needs of patients and ensuring clinical practice is safe and professional. Students are in the practice setting to learn, however, their education is a secondary feature of the learning environment. The educator/mentor will be doing their job and at the same time maximising opportunities to ensure students learn.",
                            "space_after": false
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "text-paragraph",
                            "text": "Educators and mentors typically expect students to be prepared for the practice environment (Clouder and Adefila 2017). At the University students will be exposed to a lot of a theoretical information, providing the background they need for learning on practice; educators and mentors provide the teaching in practice. In practice, students have the opportunity to acquire the skills of the profession and assess their learning."
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "subtitle": "Students with Disabilities",
                    "components": [
                        {
                            "type": "text-paragraph",
                            "space_after": false,
                            "text": "Students with disabilities are often anxious about placements, this apprehension may result in mistakes or poor communication. Educators and mentors may not understand how students learn and do not often have the time to support students who need extra help. It is important that the educators and mentors are approachable and are able to encourage students to articulate their challenges clearly and honestly. A good educator/mentor-student relationship is essential for a successful placement."
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "text-paragraph",
                            "text": "The students and educator/mentors will need to negotiate all the challenges associated with teaching in the clinical/teaching environment. This means communicating, being responsive, approachable and professionally to work with your students."
                        }
                    ],
                    "space_after": true
                },
                {
                    "subtitle": "Tips",
                    "components": [
                        {
                            "type": "list-text",
                            "list_elements": [
                                {
                                    "text": "Set appropriate goals with your student at the beginning of the placement",
                                    "links": []
                                },
                                {
                                    "text": "Discuss how you will support the student to achieve the goals with respect to time pressure, patient safety and any needs you may have."
                                },
                                {
                                    "text": "Discuss what you expect from student and provide clear feedback."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
